<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The data samples are described by attributes age, income and student. 
The BuyClass label attribute, buy, tells whether the person buys a computer, has two distinct values, 1 (class C1) and 0 (class
C2).
The sample we want to classify i.e. <strong>test</strong> is
X = (age = A, income = H, student = 0)
We need to maximize P(X|Ci)P(Ci), for i = 1, 2.</p>
<p>P(Ci), the A Priori probability of each class, can be estimated based on the training samples:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>P(buy = 1) = 9/14</code></li>
<li><code>P(buy = 0) = 5/14</code></li>
</ul>
<p>To compute P(X|Ci), for i = 1, 2, we compute the following conditional probabilities:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>P(age = A|buy = yes)</code> $= 6/9$</li>
<li><code>P(age = A|buy = no)</code> $= 1/5$</li>
<li><code>P(income = H|buy = yes)</code> $= 4/9$</li>
<li><code>P(income = H|buy = no)</code> $= 0/5$</li>
<li><code>P(student = 0|buy = yes)</code> $= 6/9$</li>
<li><code>P(student = 0|buy = no)</code> $=2/5$</li>
</ul>
<p>Using the above probabilities, we obtain</p>
<p>P(X|buy = yes) =</p>
<p>$P(age = A|buy = yes) * P(income = H|buy = yes) * P(student = 0|buy = yes)$ 
= $(6/9) * (4/9) * (6/9)$  = 324/729 = 0.44</p>
<p>P(X|buy = no) = 0</p>
<p>To find the class that <strong>Maximizes</strong> P(X|Ci)P(Ci), we compute</p>
<ul>
<li>$P(X|buy = yes) * P(buy = yes) = 0.44 * (9/14) = 0.28$</li>
<li>$P(X|buy = no) * P(buy = no) = 0 * (5/14) = 0$</li>
</ul>
<p>Therefore, the Naive Bayes Classifier predicts that the Man who is an Adult, with a high income and is not a student will buy a Computer.</p>
